Dear Mustafa,

Thank you for clarifying and providing the actual data/code (that makes it always much easier to help).

For 1), I would have just done:

xs <- log(1:12)
sav <- predict(regpln_lnt, newmods = xs, transf=exp)
wi <- 1/sqrt(datpr$vi)
size <- 1.5 + 3.0 * (wi - min(wi))/(max(wi) - min(wi))
plot(a$t, datpr$yi, ylim=c(0.1,0.4), xlim=c(0,12), ylab="Prevalence", xlab="Years (2002+)", cex=size)
lines(exp(xs), sav$pred, col="red")
lines(exp(xs), sav$ci.lb, lty="dashed")
lines(exp(xs), sav$ci.ub, lty="dashed")
text(a$t, datpr$yi, paste(a$study), cex=0.8, pos=1)

That seems to yield the same graph as your approach.

For 2), you can therefore also do:

datmn   <- escalc(measure="MN", mi=mean, sdi=sd, ni=n, data=a)
datlnmn <- escalc(measure="MNLN", mi=mean, sdi=sd, ni=n, data=a)

res <- rma(yi, vi, data=datlnmn, mods=~ln.t)
summary(res)

xs <- log(1:10)
sav <- predict(res, newmods = xs, transf=exp)
wi <- 1/sqrt(datmn$vi)
size <- 1.5 + 3.0 * (wi - min(wi))/(max(wi) - min(wi))
plot(a$t, a$mean, ylim=c(120,135), xlim=c(1,10), ylab="Mean", xlab="Years (2002+)", cex=size)
lines(exp(xs), sav$pred, col="red")
lines(exp(xs), sav$ci.lb, lty="dashed")
lines(exp(xs), sav$ci.ub, lty="dashed")
text(a$t, a$mean, paste(a$study), cex=0.8, pos=1)

As you can see, there is measure="MNLN", which is exactly what you are looking for (this was added in version 2.0-0).

Best,
Wolfgang

